<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / International Company News: Moody's downgrades Sanwa Bank
ratings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MOODY'S, the US credit rating agency, has downgraded long-term debt ratings
of Sanwa Bank, a leading Japanese bank, to Aa3 from Aa1. The ratings of
Sanwa's subsidiaries were also lowered to Aa3.
The agency attributed the downgrade to the bank's asset quality and
contingent risks associated with affiliates, especially non-bank financial
institutions.
The move follows other recent downgrades of Japanese banks by rating
agencies. Currently, there are no banks with Aaa ratings, three banks with
Aa1, two with Aa2, and six with Aa3.
Japanese banks, which expanded rapidly under easy monetary conditions of the
late 1980s, now face deteriorating loans and increasing bankruptcies due to
the fall in land prices and the stock market slump.
Most Japanese banks were hurt by last year's spate of financial scandals,
caused by loose credit controls and reckless lending.
</TEXT>
