<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Securiguard confounds City expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SECURIGUARD confounded City expectations with a 30 per cent increase in
pre-tax profits and a sharp reduction in debt that sparked a 17p jump in the
share price to 136p.
Pre-tax profits for the year to November 3 1991 rose from Pounds 3.86m to
Pounds 5.03m on sales up 7.5 per cent at Pounds 161.6m.
Mr Alan Baldwin, chairman, said debt had been cut from Pounds 17.2m to
Pounds 12.7m after payment of a Pounds 1.9m installment for the acquisition
of Madison Building Services group, increasing interest cover to over three
times.
Most of this reduction came from reducing the level of debtor days as
management focused more time on existing businesses rather than new
acquisitions.
The core security and cleaning activities in the UK grew strongly. Trading
profits expanded 22 per cent to Pounds 3.8m for security services, while
cleaning rose 16 per cent to Pounds 1.62m.
In the US, where the company was suffering from a more serious recession,
trading profits fell 18 per cent to Pounds 1.8m on sales 24 per cent higher
at Pounds 49.6m.
A reorganised overnight parcel delivery service increased its profits on
reduced sales as the volume of 'next-day' deliveries carried by City Link
networks grew by more than 40 per cent.
The weak link remained the personnel service division where losses were
slightly reduced to Pounds 700,000 following cost cutting, but on sales down
from Pounds 18.3m to Pounds 12.9m.
Mr Baldwin said contracts won in Europe would reduce the losses to under
Pounds 500,000 this year, a level that justified the decision not to close
the division.
Earnings per share rose 21 per cent to 17p (14p) and the final dividend is
raised to 5.3p, giving a total up from 8p to 8.5p.
COMMENT
Securiguard has incurred its share of City wrath in the last couple of years
for letting debt rise too high and for surprising the market with profits
warnings. Last year's sharp reduction in debt will go a long way towards
regaining confidence. Even though it will be difficult to repeat the debt
reduction by further squeezing working capital, fewer acquisitions should
mean interest cover can again increase. Concerns remain about the the
personnel services sector where the only signs of improvement come from
additional contracts in Europe rather than an upturn in the industry.
Nevertheless, estimates of pre-tax profits of Pounds 5.7m for 1991 seem
conservative. This would give earnings per share of 19.2p and a prospective
multiple still languishing at a modest 7. The stock may not, however, be
fully priced until bridges are fully rebuilt with the City.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-10935</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBDCGABUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920204
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 92 / UK Company News: CRT defies downturn in sector with 6% rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CRT, the consultancy, recruitment and training company, defied the downturn
in its sector with a 5.6 per cent rise to Pounds 2.61m in pre-tax profits
for the six months to October 31.
The interims mark the first set of accounts to be released which show CRT -
created through the reverse takeover of textile manufacturer Smallshaw in
1989 - in its virtually finished form. Smallshaw's knitwear businesses were
sold in the latter part of last year.
'CRT is now actually happening, whereas previously it was a concept,' said
Mr Barrie Clark, finance director. In the last two years, the group has paid
more than Pounds 20m for seven companies.
The pre-tax figure was struck on turnover 7 per cent higher at nearly Pounds
20m, on a pro forma basis, and compared with Pounds 2.47m. During the six
months CRT made two acquisitions, Pitman Office Training for Pounds 2.2m,
and Doctus, the management consultancy, for a nominal sum. Pitman, which
incurred losses last year, had contributed profits of about Pounds 100,000,
said Mr Karl Chapman, chief executive.
Of the group's three divisions, the decline in general recruitment had been
offset by the demand for workers in information technology. 'We are doing as
badly as everyone else in general recruitment,' he said.
However, the training division - which accounted for50 per cent of sales and
80 per cent of profits - had shown steady progress. Profits were held back
by a switch in the method of fee payment to a performance-related basis.
This meant CRT's group profits would be more weighted towards the second
half, Mr Chapman said, as payments came in when students achieved
qualifications.
The consultancy side, which was formed from the Doctus acquisition and
included for three months, had performed to expectations.
Earnings per share rose to 3.47p (3.19p). The interim dividend is raised
from 0.5p to 0.575p.
