<TEXT>
ITV has a startlingly imaginative schedule. At 8.00 it offers a programme
about the police, The Bill, one of the regular episodes in its soap opera
based upon a London police station. At 9.00 there is a programme about the
police: The Murder Squad, first of a seven-part fly-on-the-wall documentary
series about Scotland Yard's murder investigations. Then at 10.40 there is a
programme about the police: First Tuesday offers a documentary about a New
York policeman who works on the city's subway.
Lighthouse-keepers? Farmers? Anaesthetists? Yes, yes, ITV will be coming to
them, if not next week perhaps next century.
The French National Front and its leader, Jean-Marie Le Pen, are the subject
of BBC2's foreign affairs series, Assignment (7.45), which points out that
there is nothing new about extreme right wing politics in France (or among
mankind in general, of course).
Without Walls continues its series of conversations about the general state
of the world of ideas as we approach the year 2000. Tonight Salman Rushdie
is among those who discuss the significance of the collapse of communism in
eastern Europe (9.00 C4).
