FT  04 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: News in Brief
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSING: Council rent arrears stood at Pounds 430m at the end of March 1991,
a Pounds 70m rise on the previous year, Housing Minister Sir George Young
said last night.
The figure, given in a Commons written reply, represented 8.5 per cent of
the total sum collectable in 1990-91.
Sir George said London councils accounted for Pounds 200m, nearly half of
English arrears and the capital included eight of the ten authorities with
the poorest performances.
*****
CIVIL SERVICE: The government is to launch at least a dozen more Civil
Service agencies in April. That will bring the proportion of civil servants
working fully along lines laid down in the Next Steps programme to 50 per
cent.
*****
ARTS: Labour yesterday accused the government of neglecting a 'great jewel
in the British crown' by cutting the British Library's acquisitions budget
by 41 per cent in real terms over four years.
Mr Tim Renton, arts minister, said it was up to the Library to decide what
proportion of its grant in aid should be earmarked for acquisitions.
