FT  04 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Party leaders seek to step back
from rows - Election campaigning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE leadership of the three main parties took a step back yesterday from the
bitterness of the weekend's campaigning, with appeals from party leaders for
the political debate to return to the issues.
Along with the row over the break-ins at party offices, there was still some
fall-out from claims that Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, had been
'smeared' by a story in The Sunday Times giving details of a discussion he
held with the Soviet ambassador in 1984.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, made it clear he was keen that the
election should be fought on the policy issues rather than personalities.
For the Liberal Democrats, Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, and campaign
organiser Mr Des Wilson proposed an all-party meeting of the campaign
managers to agree some ground rules.
Labour claimed, however, that the prime minister's attitude was belied by Mr
Chris Patten, the Tory party chairman. Mr Patten yesterday wrote to Mr Roy
Hattersley, Labour's deputy leader, challenging him to deny that a Labour
spokesman had indicated that Labour would try to involve Mrs Norma Major in
the election campaign.
There was some sign of a response to Mr Major's appeal in the muted reaction
of Tory backbenchers during the prime minister's Commons statement on the
United Nations summit. Tory MPs could have sought to use their questions to
exploit the Sunday Times' story, but the matter was not raised.
Labour still believes that the thrust of the Tory attack would be to
denigrate Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader.
Mr John Cunningham, the party's campaigns co-ordinator, said: 'If they want
to put a stop to personal abuse of the leader of the Labour party, why don't
they do it now?'
Speaking on BBC radio he reiterated the charge that Tory newspapers were
intent on damaging Mr Kinnock's credibility, but said that he believed the
smear campaign had now been exposed.
He added: 'We want to move on to the issues like education, housing and the
National Health Service.'
Evidence of Labour's readiness to move on came yesterday with the party's
launch of a fresh offensive against Tory policies on schools, under the
heading 'Pay as you learn'.
Mr Jack Straw, the shadow education secretary, published examples of how
parents were getting drawn into fund-raising not just for extras in their
children's schools but for items such as computers and other equipment for
the national curriculum.
If the Tories won the election, he said, 'schools in prosperous areas would
be forced to rely more and more on fund-raising, while those in poorer areas
would be forced to lower standards.'
</TEXT>
