<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 92 / Inquiry into school arson rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHILD arsonists are wreaking millions of pounds of damage to British
schools, according to insurers who will today announce their backing for a
research initiative into the problem.
The cost of damage caused by arson attacks has doubled over the past five
years and is already leading to a rethink about the design of school
buildings.
It may prompt the government to back costly new fire prevention measures.
Evidence suggests that in some areas, such as Tyneside and Strathclyde,
school arson is becoming endemic.
Municipal Mutual, the company which insures four out of five local
authorities, reports that claims from all school fires cost it more than
Pounds 57m in 1991, up from Pounds 47m in 1990 and Pounds 18m in 1987. More
than two thirds of the claims stem from fires started deliberately.
The insurer reported 84 fires costing more than Pounds 100,000 each in 1991,
compared with 51 five years ago.
Mr Larry Stokes, fire underwriting manager at Municipal Mutual, said the
average cost of school fires had risen sharply. He said this reflected the
increased use schools were making of electronic equipment such as computers
and videos.
The research is being launched by the Arson Prevention Bureau, a joint Home
Office and insurance industry initiative set up last year. The bureau has
asked a team of academics to examine the causes of the fire attacks. There
is also increasing concern among educationalists about the long-term costs
of arson such as the disruption of classes and the loss of project work and
records.
The APB investigation is also expected to look closely into ways arson can
be prevented.
It will examine possible changes in building design, the introduction of new
safety and security devices and risk management techniques already being
deployed by some headteachers and school managers.
Insurers say all schools are lagging behind the private sector in the
introduction of alarm and sprinkler systems, and protective fences.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
