<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Labour condemns training underspend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GOVERNMENT budget to provide Employment Training places for the long-term
adult unemployed in England and Wales for this financial year was underspent
by Pounds 70m in November, according to a leaked Department of Employment
document.
Some of the money, which amounts to nearly 10 per cent of the annual budget
of Pounds 802m, is to be used to meet overspending on other training
schemes, including Youth Training.
The Labour party claimed the underspend showed that the government's
training schemes were in a state of chaos.
Mr Tony Blair, Labour employment spokesman, accused the government of
raiding the ET budget to cover its guarantee to young people of a place on
Youth Training.
He said one reason for the ET underspend was that unit costs, the amount
provided to train each participant, had been held down. That had reduced the
number of employers wishing to take part.
The Department of Employment said that it was normal practice for government
departments to switch money from one budget to another.
Spending of money earmarked for ET was a matter for Training and Enterprise
Councils and there was a variety of reasons why the full budget had not been
spent, it said.
It was possible that Tecs had been particularly cautious on spending in the
early part of the year because they wanted to meet demand later. None the
less, the full year is likely to show a significant underspend and the
deparment said that adjustments to training budgets would be made in the
spring.
Separately, the Labour party issued an analysis showing that the proportion
of YT leavers entering a full-time job fell from 64 per cent in 1989-90 to
53 per cent in 1990-91. The proportion of trainees obtaining a qualification
dropped from 43 to 38 per cent.
Mr Henry McLeish, shadow employment minister, said that the analysis, which
is based on Department of Employment statistics, showed that YT was
inadequate and should be replaced.
</TEXT>
