<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 92 / City status fails to become the talk of the town: This month
the Queen is expected to announce the name of the town that will be awarded
city status to mark the 40th anniversary of her accession to the throne.
Twenty towns are competing. Emma Tucker visits Derby, which was made a city
in the Queen's Silver Jubilee year of 1977, to see what - if anything - it
has gained from its new status
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSIDE the mayor of Derby's stately office a heavy red box conceals a
much-coveted document. In ornate script a charter declares that Derby 'shall
henceforth have the status of a city and shall have all such rank,
liberties, privileges, and immunities as are incident to a city'.
'We still haven't worked out what those are,' shrugs Mr Philip O'Brian, the
mayor's secretary.
They have had since 1977 to do so. That was when the Queen last granted
civic honours to a town - but city status is apparently not all it was once
cracked up to be.
Indeed the Brightons and Croydons queueing up for the privilege to mark the
40th anniversary of the Queen's accession may find the granting of a royal
charter something of an anti-climax.
There was a time, in medieval England, when a charter gave legal
independence and some degree of self-government.
Previous charters awarded to Derby gave the town market rights (1154), power
to appoint a bailiff and a monopoly in wool dyeing (1204), and power to
appoint a coroner (1256). The 1977 charter granting the grander title of
city gave no real powers.
That is not to say that the people of Derby are indifferent to their
enhanced civic status. Councillors and those working in the prosperous
business community fall over themselves to tell you what city status has
done for Derby.
National athletics events and party political conferences have taken place
in Derby City, they boast. 'The first ever SDP conference was held in
Derby,' says Mr O'Brian.
Derby also has enough cinema screens to shame any seaside resort, town or
city. Two multiplex centres have given it a total of 20 screens for a
population of a quarter of a million.
'Never mind that they all show the same films,' says Mr Paul Farrow, chief
executive of the chamber of commerce.
At least he can feel safe in Derby, where the movies and 10-pin bowling have
kept potential lager louts off the streets. Derby's crime rate has yet to
take on city status. Recorded crimes to the end of July were about 16,000.
In nearby Nottingham, an old hand at city status, the figure was more than
double at 33,173.
One thing though, is sure. City status has helped Derby's attempts to escape
from under the shadow of Nottingham.
'Derby has always felt inferior to Nottingham,' says Mr Farrow. 'It is much
more vibrant and, from that point of view, city status was important. It
elevated us to the same level - not the same size, but the same level.'
What is more, it has given the once city-less county of Derbyshire a city.
Mr Nick Brown, Conservative leader of the city council, believes the title
has given the town better economic standing.
'What it has done more than anything is give us more status in economic
development and relocation terms,' he says.
Next year the prison service will relocate to Derby, generating about 800
local jobs. Toyota, the Japanese car manufacturer, is soon to open a plant
there. Derby's status, says Mr Brown, was probably not very significant, but
he adds that the Japanese are very conscious of history and culture.
Back in the mayor's office, another title is at stake. Derby felt just a
little short-changed in 1977 when it discovered that city status did not
include Lord Mayor status. So this year it is applying for the title which,
if granted, would apparently involve little more than altering Mr Mayor's
headed notepaper - the title does not bestow a grander chain or even furrier
robes.
'It is a name but it means a lot to us really,' says Mr John Keith, the
mayor. 'Derby is the largest-populated city that hasn't got a Lord Mayor.'
While the Europeans might not make much of the permutations of mayoral
status, Mr O'Brian says the title of city helps when talking to Europeans.
'City gives the impression of infrastructure.'
Mr Roger Waterhouse, head of Derby College of Higher Education, says the
title is all to do with image.
'Previously you felt that if anybody came here they were doing Derby a
favour,' he says.
Mr Waterhouse has a vested interest. The college is currently applying for
polytechnic status. Under legislation going through parliament, any
polytechnic will be able to call itself a university, so the once sleepy
town may soon be the proud possessor of the City of Derby University.
For all the enthusiastic talk from those running the place, Derby people
have a reputation for straight-talking. The mayor warned that out on the
street people would be likely to treat city status with healthy scepticism.
He was right.
'It hasn't made any difference, to be honest,' said a bemused shop
attendant, scratching his head trying to remember 1977.
Mr Donald Eddison, who has lived in Derby for 30 years, was less kind.
'City? That's like calling the East Midlands airport international,' he
said.
WILLIAM HILL, the book-maker, has closed its book on the competition to be a
new city. Chelmsford and Brighton are favourites amid rumours that they are
the only two to have made a shortlist.
The Home Office, which will make the recommendation to the Queen, refuses to
confirm that a shortlist exists. It will not discuss the criteria for
selection, but three factors will be critical: a population of at least
250,000, some history and trade and cultural significance. Having a
cathedral or university is no longer necessary.
Other bidders that have had strong backing include Shrewsbury, Blackburn,
Wolverhampton, Guildford, Ipswich and Preston. Outsiders include Colchester,
Milton Keynes, Northampton, and Croydon. A rank outsider is Telford.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
