<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 92 / Companies warned on reporting standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY 240 companies have failed to comply with a statutory requirement on
financial reporting in their most recent annual accounts.
Under a 1989 amendment to the 1985 Companies Act, companies must state in
their annual report that the accounts have been prepared in accordance with
applicable accounting standards.
The Financial Reporting Review Panel, the recently created monitor of
accounting standards, has so far warned 238 companies that their most recent
accounts fail to comply.
Mr Sydney Treadgold, secretary to the panel, emphasised that the companies
had not necessarily contravened accounting standards but had failed to make
the statement.
Several companies made the statement and wrongly assumed that they no longer
needed to disclose full details of accounting policies. The panel sought
legal advice and last week issued a notice making clear that companies must
provide the statement and details of accounting policies.
Last week the panel issued its first reprimands against three companies that
breached accounting standards: Ultramar, the oil and gas group now owned by
Lasmo; Williams Holdings, the industrial conglomerate; and Shield Group, the
property developer and estate agent.
</TEXT>
