FT  03 FEB 92 / NatWest expects interest-rate fall
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
INTEREST RATES will come down in April with further cuts likely throughout
the year, according to Mr David Kern, National Westminster Bank's chief
economist.
In this month's issue of NatWest's Economic and Financial Outlook he says:
'The risk of higher rates to defend sterling has diminished considerably and
the next move will be a 0.5 (percentage point) cut in April. Thereafter,
gradual base-rate declines are expected, to 9 per cent by the end of 1992
and to 8.5 per cent by 1993.'
Mr Kern predicts that gross domestic product will stagnate in the first half
of this year, but a slow upturn will start in the second half.
