FT  03 FEB 92 / Tories scorn Scots backing for home rule
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR IAN LANG, the Scottish secretary, has dismissed the recent upsurge of
support for Scottish independence as a temporary 'flicker of interest'.
In a speech to Scottish Conservatives at the weekend he said Labour's plans
for a Scottish parliament had failed to stand up to detailed scrutiny and,
if implemented, would become 'an engine-room for complete separation which
the Scottish National party seeks'.
He added that the SNP's aim to make Scotland an independent country in the
European Community would be 'the worst of all worlds'.
Last week an ICM opinion poll indicated that 50 per cent of Scots wanted
independence, the highest level ever.
Mr Donald Dewar, Mr Lang's Labour shadow, accused the secretary of state of
fuelling Scottish nationalism by an 'arrogant and obstinate' stance on home
rule. He said: 'If he is genuinely worried about nationalism, he should not
be stoking the fire in this way.'
Mr Jim Sillars, SNP MP for Glasgow Govan, shrugged off the idea that Scots
did not particularly care about independence - in spite of a recent poll in
which independence was ranked sixth in importance behind issues such as
unemployment and the National Health Service.
On TV-am he said the SNP had managed to persuade people that independence
was the key to meeting social and economic needs.
A System Three opinion poll in Saturday's Glasgow Herald newspaper showed
support for Labour at 38 per cent in Scotland, a drop of 9 percentage points
on early January. The SNP was up 5 points at 26 per cent. Support for the
Conservatives rose 2 points to 23 per cent, 1 point short of their share of
the vote in the 1987 general election.
Liberal Democrat supporters are split three ways over a hung parliament,
according to a poll for BBC Television's Panorama programme tonight. NOP
found that of 504 supporters, 29 per cent wanted a post-election deal with
the Tories, 29 per cent with Labour and 31 per cent no deal with either.
A separate poll, of nearly 1,000 voters, found 56 per cent supporting
proportional representation, compared with 34 per cent wishing to keep the
existing first-past-the-post system for elections.
</TEXT>
