<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 92 / Serbs in Croatia hold out on UN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HARDLINE leaders of a Serb enclave in the republic of Croatia denied last
night that they had dropped their objections to a UN peace-keeping plan.
According to the Serb-dominated rump Yugoslav presidency, after three days
of talks in Belgrade the self-proclaimed republic of Krajina, in southern
Croatia, had accepted the UN plan to send 10,000 peace-keepers to Croatia
In a statement reported by the Belgrade-based Tanjug news agency, the
presidency said that the president of Krajina's parliament, Mr Mile Paspalj,
had accepted the plan on behalf of the parliament in the absence of Mr Milan
Babic, Krajina's president.
But later, in a statement signed by Mr Babic and issued by the Krajina
government office in Belgrade, the Krajina government said it had not agreed
to accept UN peace-keepers on its territory.
A spokesman at the office said Mr Paspalj did not have the authority to sign
any agreements on behalf of the Krajina government.
In more than 30 hours of closed-door talks Serb leaders from throughout
Yugoslavia were unable to persuade Mr Babic to agree to the UN plan.
In a sign of the widening rift with Serbia, under President Slobodan
Milosevic, Mr Babic accused the rump Yugoslav presidency of plotting a coup
d'etat to unseat his government.
While Mr Babic's opposition has blocked the Serbian side, Croat leaders have
also objected to the UN plan.
They insist that the mandate for peacekeepers should not be extended for
more than a year, fearing long-term deployment would mean the permanent loss
of Krajina to Serbia. The federal army and Serb irregulars currently control
about one-third of Croatia.
Mr Babic says the Serb-controlled federal army must remain in Krajina even
after peacekeepers are deployed. He insists Serb paramilitary units should
not be disarmed unless Croat forces are disbanded.
</TEXT>
