FT  03 FEB 92 / Parker Pen auction may raise up to Pounds 300m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PARKER Pen, the writing instrument maker, is for sale in a global auction
likely to raise up to Pounds 300m, its advisers said yesterday.
After three previous attempts to sell the company, this is the first time
the international group has been marketed throughout the world.
Mr Gerry Grimstone, head of the disposals unit at Schroders, the UK merchant
bank, which is handling the sale, has drawn up a list of potential buyers in
Europe, America and Asia.
Parker is expected to make operating profits of about Pounds 33m this year,
after investing Pounds 1m in a new stationery line, on sales of around
Pounds 180m. It has borrowings of Pounds 54m. The group's managers, who
bought out the group in 1985, are likely to become millionaires following
the sale.
Parker failed twice to float itself on the stock exchange in the 1980s. It
agreed a friendly takeover with Pentland in 1988, only to see the Pounds
180m deal fall apart when its institutional backers objected. Mr Jacques
Margry, chief executive, was then quoted as saying: 'I do not want any more
offers.'
However, advisers to Parker said Mr Margry and his management now want to
leave the group after seven years in which they have concentrated on brand
promotion and taking the group's image up-market. A sale by flotation was
rejected because Schroders expects to raise more through a trade sale.
Parker's advisers stressed that at the time of the aborted Pentland deal the
group was not marketed to any other company.
