<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Perhaps Wildlife On One (BBC1, 8.30) ought to be re-named 'Nature Red In
Tooth And Claw'. Tonight, as so often, the programme is concerned with
depredation: the annual return of shoals of fish called the eulachon to the
coastal waters of Alaska and their attack by humpback whales, bald eagles,
seals and sea lions.
We are promised that Bye Bye Columbus on BBC2 (9.00) will not be just
another chunk of 500th anniversary idolatry, but a sharp, surreal and
offbeat drama in which Columbus, played by Daniel Massey, reviews his own
achievements in conversation with his parrot. The 50-minute drama is written
by Peter Barnes and the starry cast includes Simon Callow, Jack Shepherd as
the parrot, Harriet Walter and Timothy West.
Channel 4's impressive series documenting The Falklands War reaches its
fourth and last part (9.00). In anticipation of a possible hung parliament,
Panorama turns its attention to 'The Third Man', Paddy Ashdown, who keeps on
talking about people voting for a 'balanced parliament' as though a British
voter was allowed to vote for anything other than one person and
consequently one party.
</TEXT>
