FT  01 FEB 92 / Anger as bill for disabled fails
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BILL to establish a powerful disablement commission failed in the Commons
yesterday, in spite of support from MPs of all parties.
The Civil Rights (Disabled Persons) Bill, piloted by Mr Alf Morris, MP for
Wythenshawe and a former Labour minister for the disabled, failed to win a
second reading when the debate ran out of time after an hour and 55 minutes
when the House finished for business.
A closure vote, necessary to move the bill on, was turned down as the debate
had lasted less than two hours. A vote on whether to give the bill a second
reading could not be taken automatically as an MP - Mr Robert Hayward, Tory
member for Kingswood - was still speaking.
Furious opposition MPs rounded on Mr Hayward, charging him with
dishonourable conduct. He had said he would not talk the bill out. The
bill's effective death knell had been sounded earlier when Mr Nicholas
Scott, social security minister, withheld government backing, saying he
remained 'benevolently neutral'.
Mr Paul Boateng, Labour MP for Brent South, said the government's neutrality
amounted to 'the kiss of death'. A bill permitting nurses, midwives and
health visitors to prescribe certain drugs without doctors' approval won a
second reading yesterday.
