FT  01 FEB 92 / China spurns human rights interference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LI PENG, China's hard-line premier largely blamed for the bloody 1989
crackdown on the democracy movement, insisted in the UN last night that
human rights were a national matter not subject to external criteria.
Addressing the Security Council at its summit meeting, he said China valued
human rights and was ready to discuss them and co-operate with other states,
'while reserving differences'. China opposed interference in internal
affairs 'using human rights as an excuse'.
President George Bush arranged a meeting with Li in New York last night,
ignoring sharp criticism by members of the Congress and others who said he
ought first to have demanded Chinese concessions on human rights and other
issues.
Mr James Baker, US secretary of state, had said earlier that the US intended
to press China to fulfill commitments to curb exports of missile technology.
Mr Bush would be seeking a letter confirming China's pledge to sign the
non-proliferation treaty and observe the guidelines of the missile
technology control regime (MCTR).
Chinese officials have said they will abide by provision of the MTCR but
only if the Bush administration lifts sanctions on the sale of American
satellite parts and high speed computers. These sanctions were imposed last
spring after the US learned that China had secretly delivered launchers for
M-11 missiles to Pakistan.
